Since you are using Ansible to configure properties, the microservice is likely running as a Docker container or a systemd service.
1. Check Running Containers: If it’s a containerized app, use: docker ps
  Look for the image name from your ACR and check the "STATUS" column (it should say Up X minutes).
2. Check Service Status: If Ansible installs it as a native Linux service: systemctl status <service-name>
3. Verify Logs: To see if the app started correctly without internal errors: docker logs -f <container_id>  (for Docker)
4. Network Check: Verify the service is listening on the expected port: netstat -tuln | grep <port_number>

Azure Container Registry (ACR):
  Navigate to your ACR resource ->  Under Services -> click Repositories.
  Find your service name and click it to see the Tags. Verify that a new tag (usually the Jenkins build number or a timestamp) was pushed recently.

Virtual Machine / App Service: (extra)
  If you are deploying to an Azure VM, check the Networking tab to ensure the ports defined in your Ansible YAML are open in the Network Security Group (NSG).
  Check Insights/Metrics to see CPU and memory heartbeats, which indicate the service is actually doing work.

Core Components of  Pipeline:
1. Git Repo - Holds the Source Code and the Ansible Playbooks.
2. Jenkins - 	The Orchestrator. It triggers the build, runs Docker commands to build the image, and executes the Ansible task.
3. Ansible	- The Configuration Manager. It ensures the Linux server has the right environment variables, secrets, and pulls the correct image version from ACR.
4. ACR	- The private storage for your Docker images. Jenkins pushes here; the Server pulls from here.
5. Linux Server	- The Host. The final destination where the code actually executes.

To verify : curl -I http://localhost:<port>/health

1. The Authentication Command: az acr login --name feidtifacr001 --subscription <sub-id>
    What it does: Authenticates your local Docker/Podman daemon with your private Azure Container Registry (ACR).
    Why it's helpful: Without this, your local machine won't have the "keys" to pull the microservice images stored in Azure. 
                      It ensures that when Ansible tries to deploy the app, it doesn't get an "Access Denied" error from the registry.

2. The Deployment Playbooks: The ansible-playbook commands are the "brains" of the operation.
                            Ansible uses these YAML files to ensure your local environment matches the required state.
A. Project Setup & Deployment: ansible-playbook -i ... test-setup.yml deploy-from-project.yml -e project_dir=/app/dev/<your project>
    test-setup.yml: Likely prepares the infrastructure (creates namespaces, sets up storage, or verifies dependencies).
    deploy-from-project.yml: This is the main action. It pulls the code/image from the directory you specified (-e project_dir) and pushes it to your target environment.  
        -e (Extra Vars): This allows you to tell Ansible exactly which microservice project you want to work on without changing the code of the playbook.
B. Environment Configuration: ansible-playbook -i ... dev-sandbox.yml and k8-vdi-env.yml
dev-sandbox.yml: Sets up a "Sandbox" (a safe, isolated area) on your Linux machine or AKS cluster so you can test changes without breaking the main development branch.
    k8-vdi-env.yml: Configures the specific Kubernetes environment for a VDI (Virtual Desktop Infrastructure) setup.
                It likely handles the networking and permissions needed for your local Linux machine to talk to the Kubernetes API.

How this helps your local setup:
Consistency: By using these commands, you ensure your local Linux machine is configured exactly like the production server.
Speed: Instead of manually setting up database connections or environment properties, Ansible does it in seconds.
Isolation: The "sandbox" playbooks allow you to break things locally while you experiment with the Ansible YAML properties without affecting other developers.

To verify these in the Azure Portal, follow these steps:
1. Check Exposed Endpoints (Services & Ingress): This is where you find the External IP or DNS name for your microservice.
    Navigate to: Azure Portal > Kubernetes services > Select your Cluster.
    Go to: Under the Kubernetes resources section on the left, click Services and ingresses.
    What to look for:
    Services tab: Look for your service name. 
                  If the type is LoadBalancer, you will see an External IP listed. 
                  This is the public entry point. 
    Ingresses tab: If you are using an Ingress Controller (like Nginx), look here for the Host or Address. 
                   This usually maps multiple microservices to one IP via different paths (e.g., /api/user, /api/order).
2. Check the "Workloads" (Is the code actually running?): Even if an IP is exposed, the service won't work if the container failed to start.
      Navigate to: Cluster > Kubernetes resources > Workloads.
      Check Status: Look at the Deployments or Pods tab.
                    You want to see a green checkmark or Ready: 1/1.
                    If it says ImagePullBackOff, it means AKS couldn't talk to your ACR (check your az acr login permissions).
                    If it says CrashLoopBackOff, the code is failing internally (check Live Logs in the portal).
3. Verify the Container Image in ACR: To ensure Jenkins actually pushed the latest version:
      Navigate to: Azure Portal > Container registries > Select feidtifacr001.
      Go to: Under Services, click Repositories.
      Action: Find your specific microservice repository. Click on it to see the Tags. 
              The top tag should match the timestamp or build ID from your recent Jenkins/Ansible run.

Get Public URL/IP -> AKS > Services and ingresses -> External IP / Frontend IP
Check App Health  -> AKS > Workloads > Pods       -> Status (Running) & Live Logs
Verify Image Push -> ACR > Repositories            -> Tag (Timestamp/Build ID)
Check Config/Secrets  -> AKS > Configuration        -> ConfigMaps / Secrets

1. The Cluster:
          The Cluster is the entire "Gated Community." It is a group of virtual machines (Nodes) working together, managed by Azure.  
          In your case: This is the resource you see in the Azure Portal that contains all your dev/sandbox environments.
2. The Node:
          A Node is a single "Apartment Building" (a Virtual Machine) within the cluster.
          In your case: When you run ansible-playbook -i ... vdi, your inventory is likely pointing to these nodes. 
                        They provide the CPU and RAM that actually run your microservice.
3. The Pod:
          A Pod is the "Individual Apartment." It is the smallest unit in Kubernetes. 
          It wraps your Docker container (the image from your ACR) and gives it an internal IP address.
          In your case: If your microservice crashes, the Pod is what gets restarted. 
                        You check Pod status in the Workloads section of the Azure Portal.
4. The Deployment:
          A Deployment is the "Building Blueprint" or the "Property Manager." 
          It defines how many copies (replicas) of a Pod should be running and which version of the image from feidtifacr001 should be used.
          In your case: Your deploy-from-project.yml Ansible playbook likely creates or updates this Deployment. 
                        If you want to scale your service from 1 instance to 3, you update the Deployment.
5. The Service:
          A Service is the "Front Gate/Intercom."
          Since Pods are constantly being destroyed and recreated (getting new internal IPs), the Service provides a permanent IP address or DNS name so other apps can find your microservice.
          In your case: This is what "exposes" your app. When you looked at Services and ingresses in the portal, you were looking at this layer to find the External IP.

How they connect to your Ansible commands:
      Your Ansible Playbook tells the Cluster to create a Deployment.
      That Deployment pulls an image from ACR and puts it into a Pod.
      The Pod runs on a Node.
      A Service is created so you can access that Pod from your browser or another microservice.
